\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Local and Robust Self testing using trapped ions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Xiaomin etc.., Atul Singh Arora, Kishor Bharti, Adan Cabello, Kwek Leong Chuan
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We provide experimental implementation of KCBS self-testing scheme.
 Theoretical tools are supplemented to render the results in 
\shape italic
Physical Review Letters 122 (25), 250403 
\shape default
practical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exclusivity graph approach to contextuality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Robust self-testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Verifying the assumptions experimentally
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The self-testing results in reference
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bharti2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 hinges on three assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The measurements are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sharp
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Sharp measurements are outcome-repeatable and minimally disturbing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The measurements follow the compatibility relation according to an odd cycle
 graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The black box has no more memory than its information-carrying capacity.
 Each box is used once, and there is an unlimited supply of them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the experiments, we verify sharpness (assumption 1) and compatibility
 (assumption 2) based on the techniques in reference
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "leupold2018sustained"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To quantify sharpness of an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, it is instructive to quantify the probability of getting the same outcome
 corresponding to two consecutive measurements of the same measurement i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}.$
\end_inset

 The appropriate mathematical expression for the same could be given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{\mu}=\frac{\sum_{a_{1}}N\left(A_{\mu}=a_{1},A_{\mu}=a_{1}\right)}{N\left(A_{\mu},A_{\mu}\right)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N(.)$
\end_inset

quantifies the number of instances corresponding to the expression inside
 its following bracket.
 Coming back to assumption 2, the necessary conditions for compatibility
 are the absence of context-signalling as well as lack of influence of a
 precedding compatible measurement on the statistics of an observable.
 The forward context-signalling is quantified by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{u,v,w;i}^{f}=\frac{N_{i}\left(A_{\nu},A_{u}=a_{1}\right)}{N_{i}\left(A_{\nu},A_{u}\right)}-\frac{N_{i}\left(A_{w},A_{u}=a_{1}\right)}{N_{i}\left(A_{w},A_{u}\right)},\label{eq:SigF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whereas the backward context-signalling is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{u,v,w;i}^{b}=\frac{N_{i}\left(A_{u}=a_{1},A_{\nu}\right)}{N_{i}\left(A_{\nu},A_{u}\right)}-\frac{N_{i}\left(A=a_{1},A_{w}\right)}{N_{i}\left(A_{w},A_{u}\right)}.\label{eq:SigB}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is worth mentioning that the expressions for the forward and backward
 context-signalling are defined for some fixed input state 
\begin_inset Formula $i.$
\end_inset

 In case of no-context signalling, the value of both the expressions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SigB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SigF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is zero.
 Regarding assumption 3, we haven't closed the memory loop-hole.
 (TODO: Add the compatibility check via contextuality-by-default approach)
\end_layout

