\begin_layout Section
Theoretical Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to provide a lower bound on fidelity for the experimental results
 in section 2.
 The following steps are required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regularizing the experimental statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bharti2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, authors assume that the measurement operators follow cyclic compatibility
 structure.
 However, this need not be true in the real life experimental scenario.
 Thus, the experimental data may not belong to quantum set due to finite
 statistics and violation of the cyclic compatibility structure.
 This demands a regularization of the experimental data for the theoretical
 analysis.
 Here, regularization means finding the statistics which is closest to our
 experimental statistics and belongs to the quantum set.
 The
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Providing a lower bound on the fidelity from regularized measurement statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constructing the isometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A swap circuit between two qudit registers is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $S=TUVU$
\end_inset

 where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\mathbb{I}\otimes\sum_{k}\vert-k\rangle\langle k\vert
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\sum_{k=0}^{d-1}P^{k}\otimes\vert k\rangle\langle k\vert
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\sum_{k=0}^{d-1}\vert k\rangle\langle k\vert\otimes P^{-k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\sum_{k=0}^{d-1}\vert k+1\rangle\langle k\vert.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a translation operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TUVU, Localizing matrix etc....
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Deriving the expression for fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left\{ \bar{\Pi_{i}}\right\} _{i\in V},\vert\bar{\psi}\rangle\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the ideal configuration and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left\{ \Pi_{i}\right\} ,\vert\psi\rangle\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the candidate configuration.
 Our expression for the fidelity for the aforementioned configurations is
 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(\alpha,\beta\right)=\alpha\sum_{i\in V}\langle\bar{\psi\vert}\bar{\Pi_{i}}\Pi_{i}\vert\psi\rangle+\beta\langle\bar{\psi\vert}\psi\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and are weights on fidelitiy for states and measured states respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total fidelity for state and projectors for odd 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-cycle scenario in the ideal case is 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Providing the lower bound on fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NPA analoge for theta body
\end_layout

